SIMPLE: watch
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Watch
<hw>Watch</hw> <pr>(w⟦ocr⟧ch)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>wacche</ets>, AS. <ets>w⟦ae⟧cce</ets>, fr. <ets>wacian</ets> to
wake; akin to D. <ets>wacht</ets>, <ets>waak</ets>, G. <ets>wacht</ets>,
<ets>wache</ets>. ⟦root⟧134. See <er>Wake</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos>
]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of watching; forbearance of sleep; vigil;
wakeful, vigilant, or constantly observant attention; close observation;
guard; preservative or preventive vigilance; formerly, a watching or
guarding by night.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Shepherds keeping <qex>watch</qex> by night.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All the long night their mournful <qex>watch</qex> they keep.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Watch</xex> was formerly distinguished from
<xex>ward</xex>, the former signifying a watching or guarding by
<xex>night</xex>, and the latter a watching, guarding, or protecting by
<xex>day</xex> Hence, they were not unfrequently used together,
especially in the phrase <xex>to keep watch and ward</xex>, to denote
continuous and uninterrupted vigilance or protection, or both watching
and guarding. This distinction is now rarely recognized,
<xex>watch</xex> being used to signify a watching or guarding both by
night and by day, and <xex>ward</xex>, which is now rarely used, having
simply the meaning of <xex>guard</xex>, or <xex>protection</xex>,
without reference to time.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Still, when she slept, he kept both <qex>watch and ward</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Ward</qex>, guard, or <qex>custodia</qex>, is chiefly applied
to the daytime, in order to apprehend rioters, and robbers on the
highway . . . <qex>Watch</qex>, is properly applicable to the night
only, . . . and it begins when <qex>ward</qex> ends, and ends when that
begins.</q> <rj><qau>Blackstone.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One who watches, or those who watch; a watchman, or
a body of watchmen; a sentry; a guard.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Pilate said unto them, Ye have a <qex>watch</qex>; go your way,
make it as sure as ye can.</q> <rj><qau>Matt. xxvii. 65.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The post or office of a watchman; also, the place
where a watchman is posted, or where a guard is kept.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He upbraids Iago, that he made him⟦br⟧
Brave me upon the <qex>watch</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The period of the night during which a person does
duty as a sentinel, or guard; the time from the placing of a sentinel
till his relief; hence, a division of the night.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I did stand my <qex>watch</qex> upon the hill.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Might we but hear . . . ⟦br⟧
Or whistle from the lodge, or village cock⟦br⟧
Count the night <qex>watches</qex> to his feathery dames.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A small timepiece, or chronometer, to be carried
about the person, the machinery of which is moved by a spring.</def><--
or electric or electronic mechanisms. -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Watches are often distinguished by the kind of
escapement used, as an <stype>anchor watch</stype>, a <stype>lever
watch</stype>, a <stype>chronometer watch</stype>, etc. (see the Note
under <er>Escapement</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, 3); also, by the kind of case,
as a <stype>gold</stype> or <stype>silver watch</stype>, an
<stype>open-faced watch</stype>, a <stype>hunting watch</stype>, or
<stype>hunter</stype>, etc.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>An allotted portion
of time, usually four hour for standing watch, or being on deck ready
for duty. Cf. <er>Dogwatch</er>.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>That part,
usually one half, of the officers and crew, who together attend to the
working of a vessel for an allotted time, usually four hours. The
watches are designated as the <stype>port watch</stype>, and the
<stype>starboard watch</stype>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Anchor watch</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>a detail
of one or more men who keep watch on deck when a vessel is at
anchor.</cd> -- <col><b>To be on the watch</b></col>, <cd>to be looking
steadily for some event.</cd> -- <col><b>Watch and ward</b></col>
<fld>(Law)</fld>, <cd>the charge or care of certain officers to keep a
watch by night and a guard by day in towns, cities, and other districts,
for the preservation of the public peace.</cd> <au>Wharton.</au>
<au>Burrill.</au> -- <col><b>Watch and watch</b></col>
<fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>the regular alternation in being on watch and
off watch of the two watches into which a ship's crew is commonly
divided.</cd> -- <col><b>Watch barrel</b></col>, <cd>the brass box in a
watch, containing the mainspring.</cd> -- <col><b>Watch bell</b></col>
<fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>a bell struck when the half-hour glass is run
out, or at the end of each half hour.</cd> <au>Craig.</au> --
<col><b>Watch bill</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>a list of the
officers and crew of a ship as divided into watches, with their
stations.</cd> <au>Totten.</au> -- <col><b>Watch case</b></col>, <cd>the
case, or outside covering, of a watch; also, a case for holding a watch,
or in which it is kept.</cd> -- <col><b>Watch chain</b></col>. <cd>Same
as <cref>watch guard</cref>, below.</cd> -- <col><b>Watch
clock</b></col>, <cd>a watchman's clock; see under
<er>Watchman</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Watch fire</b></col>, <cd>a fire
lighted at night, as a signal, or for the use of a watch or guard.</cd>
-- <col><b>Watch glass</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>A concavo-convex
glass for covering the face, or dial, of a watch; -- also called
<altname>watch crystal</altname>.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>
<cd>A half-hour glass used to measure the time of a watch on
deck.</cd><-- (c) <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <cd>A round concavo-convex glass of
shallow depth used for certain manipulations of chemicals in a
laboratory.</cd> --> -- <col><b>Watch guard</b></col>, <cd>a chain or
cord by which a watch is attached to the person.</cd> -- <col><b>Watch
gun</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>a gun sometimes fired on shipboard
at 8 p. m., when the night watch begins.</cd> -- <col><b>Watch
light</b></col>, <cd>a low-burning lamp used by watchers at night;
formerly, a candle having a rush wick.</cd> -- <col><b>Watch
night</b></col>, <cd>The last night of the year; -- so called by the
Methodists, Moravians, and others, who observe it by holding religious
meetings lasting until after midnight.</cd> -- <col><b>Watch
paper</b></col>, <cd>an old-fashioned ornament for the inside of a watch
case, made of paper cut in some fanciful design, as a vase with flowers,
etc.</cd> -- <col><b>Watch tackle</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>a
small, handy purchase, consisting of a tailed double block, and a single
block with a hook.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Watch</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Watch
<hw>Watch</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[Cf. AS.
<ets>w⟦oe⟧ccan</ets>, <ets>wacian</ets>. ⟦root⟧134. See <er>Watch</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>, <er>Wake</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos> ]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To be awake; to be or continue without sleep; to
wake; to keep vigil.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I have two nights <qex>watched</qex> with you.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Couldest thou not <qex>watch</qex> one hour ?</q> <rj><qau>Mark
xiv. 37.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To be attentive or vigilant; to give heed; to be on
the lookout; to keep guard; to act as sentinel.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Take ye heed, <qex>watch</qex> and pray.</q> <rj><qau>Mark xiii.
33.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Son gave signal high⟦br⟧
To the bright minister that <qex>watched</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To be expectant; to look with expectation; to wait;
to seek opportunity.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My soul waiteth for the Lord more than they that <qex>watch</qex>
for the morning.</q> <rj><qau>Ps. cxxx. 6.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To remain awake with any one as nurse or attendant;
to attend on the sick during the night; <as>as, to <ex>watch</ex> with a
man in a fever</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>To serve the purpose of a
watchman by floating properly in its place; -- said of a buoy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To watch over</b></col>, <cd>to be cautiously observant
of; to inspect, superintend, and guard.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Watch</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Watch
<hw>Watch</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Watched</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Watching</conjf>.]</vmorph>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To give heed to; to observe the actions or motions
of, for any purpose; to keep in view; not to lose from sight and
observation; <as>as, to <ex>watch</ex> the progress of a bill in the
legislature</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Saul also sent messengers unto David's house to <qex>watch</qex>
him, and to slay him.</q> <rj><qau>1 Sam. xix. 11</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I must cool a little, and <qex>watch</qex> my opportunity.</q>
<rj><qau>Landor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In lazy mood I <qex>watched</qex> the little circles die.</q>
<rj><qau>Longfellow.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To tend; to guard; to have in keeping.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And flaming ministers, to <qex>watch</qex> and tend⟦br⟧
Their earthy charge.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Paris <qex>watched</qex> the flocks in the groves of Ida.</q>
<rj><qau>Broome.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1631 -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Watchdog</ent>⟦br⟧
